{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f7c9e19b-9e1e-4656-91f3-c74013fdc23c","content":"With MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9, you get full constructor injection support. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncDisposable, IDisposable\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private HttpClient? _httpClient;\n\n    // Synchronous init: inject TestContext via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    // Async per-test init\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        _httpClient = new HttpClient();\n        await _httpClient.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/health\");\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test...\");\n        var response = await _httpClient!.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/api\");\n        Assert.IsTrue(response.IsSuccessStatusCode);\n    }\n\n    // Async cleanup\n    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()\n    {\n        if (_httpClient is not null)\n            _httpClient.Dispose();\n        await ValueTask.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    public void Dispose() { }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points for MSTest 3.x:**\n\n| Concern | Mechanism |\n|---|---|\n| Sync init | Constructor (receives `TestContext` via DI) |\n| Async per-test init | `[TestInitialize] async Task` method |\n| Async per-class init | `[ClassInitialize] static async Task` |\n| Cleanup | `IDisposable` / `IAsyncDisposable` or `[TestCleanup]` |\n\nThe constructor injection of `TestContext` replaces the older property-setter pattern (`public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }`). Both still work, but constructor injection is preferred in v3+ as it's immutable and available immediately.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"89c13571-440d-4783-b760-e2f8e6e139e2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), constructor injection for `TestContext` is supported. Let me provide the recommended pattern.\n\nIn MSTest v3+, you can:\n1. Inject `TestContext` via the constructor\n2. Use `[TestInitialize]` for synchronous init\n3. Use `[TestInitialize]` with async Task for async init (MSTest v3 supports async `[TestInitialize]`)\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The user asks about \"both synchronous and asynchronous initialization using constructor injection for TestContext.\"\n\n\nSo the pattern is to inject `TestContext` through the constructor for synchronous setup, then use async `[TestInitialize]` methods for any asynchronous per-test initialization that needs to happen before each test runs.","outputTokens":749,"requestId":"603D:2EDED2:26094A1:28A179D:6A0311E4"},"id":"5d6f8573-571c-4f56-aafe-fd62b6b30ce1","timestamp":"2026-05-12T11:41:44.308Z","parentId":"3b99d67f-2447-42b9-8890-371f926930ef"}
